                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The best series of cookbooks for bachlors I've ever come across is the Company's Coming series and you can find a link with some recipes <a href="http://www.companyscoming.com/" target="_blank" class="postlink">-HERE-</a>. The best part is that all the recipes are simply, tasty and easy to read. For the beginning cook I highly recommend this series. 
<br />

<br />
As for your vodka sauce... I recommend you don't attempt to make your own sauce!! If you think you need help, it's probably best to avoid them for a while till you're a bit more comfortable in the kitchen as they're the hardest items to get right in my experience. Pasta is also the definitive bachlor dish so if you're hoping to make an impression I'm going to recommend something easy which comes off with a bit more pizzaz. 
<br />

<br />
If you can cook meat you're half way and pick up some chicken and BBQ it you're half way there. Now, boil up some patotoes in advance, then cut them into slices. Put some salt, pepper, olive oil on top (I add thyme as well if you like that sort of thing) of the slices and broil them in the oven till they're golden brown and flip them to do both sides. Lastly make a salad, buy a bag of 'Mixed Greens' (NOT lettuce - they just make bland salads) from your local supermarket, cut up a tomato, a red or yellow pepper, mushrooms, and either feta or havarti cheese (cheedar will do just fine as well!!) or whatever else you like in a salad and buy a simply dressing to go with it. If you you like a 'hard' vegtable like carrots then shred them. Personally I love avacado, so I use them often in salads as well and definitly think about color when assembling it.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />1010011010 - Binary of the Beast!</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
