                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I can't help you with the vodka sauce, but I can recommend a couple of good cook books in general.  Neither of us are good cooks, but we can make nice meals using those three books.
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/2920845071/qid=1088449878/sr=1-3/ref=sr_1_3/103-5369789-3507807?v=glance&s=books" target="_blank" class="postlink">Easy Cooking for Today</a>
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/292084556X/ref=pd_sim_books_1/103-5369789-3507807?v=glance&s=books" target="_blank" class="postlink">Easy Cooking for Today, Volume II</a>
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/0761128255/qid=1088450435/sr=8-1/ref=pd_ka_1/103-5369789-3507807?v=glance&s=books&n=507846" target="_blank" class="postlink">Passionate Vegetarian</a>
<br />
There is a lot of reading to this one.  We aren't vegetarian's ourselves, but some stuff in this book is nice.
<br />
Examples:
<br />
Roasty Toasty Potatoes (Carrots and Onions?)
<br />
Hungarian Sweet Potato and Potato Soup</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=554032" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://www.ageofmages.com/images/Fairy-sig.gif" border="0" /></a>
