                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Not vodka, but here's what I recommend:
<br />

<br />
Sautee finely chopped garlic (buy it fresh, that canned stuff doesn't do it here - I like a whole clove or two) and a shallot (yes, much stronger flavor than an onion) in olive oil in a pretty big pan (you'll see why it needs to be big later).
<br />

<br />
Add a can of diced tomatos (no other flavorings, with the extra juice drained out ahead of time.
<br />

<br />
Once they start to go clear, add some mushrooms, I like crimini / baby portabello, and maybe some chunks of eggplant (yummy here).   A few capers couldn't hurt either.
<br />

<br />
Once it's all cooked a few minutes, add a hearty splash of red wine.  This is a great use for leftover wine that you don't want to drink anymore.  Probably anything works fine, as long as it's flavorful.  I really liked a shiraz / cabernet sauvignon mix from Australia.  NEVER cook with "cooking wines" you find in the grocery.  These are usually flavored with extra salt, and will throw your recipe off.  Just use a decent, affordable drinking wine.
<br />

<br />
When the sauce starts to thicken (it might start to look kind of ugly and brownish - don't worry, it'll get pretty again), add some cream (those little cartons of whipping cream do the trick, though you probably just want to add a little bit).  Stir it, then add a chunk of butter and stir it in.
<br />

<br />
Drain whatever pasta you've cooked and add it to the sauce.  Stir and let it all cook together for a couple of minutes (aren't you glad you have a big pan now?).
<br />

<br />
Another tip - For pasta with a sauce, don't rinse the pasta.  Freshly cooked pasta has starch on the outside that will help the sauce stick to it.  If you rinse it, this will wash the starch off.  Also, cooking most pasta with olive oil is not recommended, as it will also click the pasta and make the sauve stick to it less.  Lasagna would be an exception, as the olive oil will make it easier to separate the noodle to lay them in the pan to make it.  Some people use recipes that let you put uncooked lasagna in the pan to cook it while baking, but that's not my bag, baby.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
